  "description": "Pure number-theoretic core of RSA modelled on the python-rsa library: encryptInt/decryptInt (modular exponentiation) plus the key-math primitives gcd/extendedGcd/inverse/crt. Every output is pinned to a UNIQUE answer by a relation against FROZEN operations (^, %, *, +, ∣, <) over an unbounded domain. encryptInt and decryptInt are characterised independently as their frozen modular-exponentiation residue (m^e)%n / (c^d)%n — the RSA round-trip decrypt(encrypt m)=m is a derived consequence, never the load-bearing spec. inverse is pinned by (x*inv)%n=1 together with the mandatory uniqueness clause inv<n. crt is pinned by the two-modulus congruence law (it reduces to each residue modulo its modulus) together with the range clause crt<∏moduli. gcd is characterised by the divisibility relation (divides both, every common divisor divides it). extendedGcd is pinned by the Bézout identity a*x+b*y=g together with g=gcd a b. Proof depth is genuine and layered: inverse correctness requires the extended-Euclidean Bézout identity, and the two-modulus CRT congruence rides on inverse correctness, so the modular-inverse algorithm is transitively forced. Concrete-vector specs anchor python-rsa's exact return values (extendedGcd 240 46 = (2,-9,47); inverse 17 3120 = 2753; crt [2,3] [3,5] = 8) as SUPPORTING anchors, not drivers. Scope: integer-level primitives only — no key generation, PKCS#1 padding, byte/blocksize handling, or ASN.1 encoding; discrete (Nat/Int), mathlib-free, no Float.",
